Introduction

With support of a Party coalition named “Brazil above everything, God above everyone” , Bolsonaro was elected, in 2018, president of Brazil for the 2019-2022 term. Having served as congress representative (“deputado federal”) for the State of Rio de Janeiro since 1991, Bolsonaro reached notoriety for his populist, sexist, homophobic, anti-human rights and often anti-democratic political views.

After 4 consecutive elections of a left party (“Labour Party”, i.e. “Partido do Trabalhadores” – PT) for the presidency of Brazil, and on the aftermath of a controversial conviction of its most prominent leader – and front runner in the election polls – on corruption charges, Bolsonaro benefited from a rise in anti-leftness sentiment and took the leadership of the poll of candidates with a manifesto that was filled with religious/Christian language and that was based on three pillars, that were directly opposed to the agenda of left/progressive groups:

  1. Liberalization of economic policy: promising deregulation, privatization and extinction of sectors of the public service;

  2. Public Security policy: a criminal reform package meant to harden convictions for crimes; exempt law enforcement officials of liability for any deaths they may cause in service; facilitate the private possession of firearms;

  3. Conservative Moral agenda: opposition of sex education in schools; opposition to policies that aim at extending equality of rights for LGBT people; opposition to pregnancy termination, even in the limited circumstances allowed in Brazilian Law (rape; health risk for woman; anencephaly of fetus); reinforcement of gender stereotypical roles.

For this project, we are interested in assessing if, and to what extent, these three axis that constitute Bolsonaro’s political agenda are also resonating in the Brazilian Senate.

Brazil’s Senate House is composed of 3 senators per State and the Federal District, totaling 81 senators. Each of their term in office last for 8 years, but the election cycle happens every 4 years, alternating the elections for 2/3 and 1/3 of the house. Theoretically speaking, the alternate election cycle should render the Senate house less sensitive to momentary waves that, if salient in a given moment, could heavily influence the course of a presidential election.

In 2018, 2/3 of the Senate chairs were elected (54 senators), while the remaining 1/3 had still half the term in office to complete.

In this project, we analyzed the corpus of Senators’ speeches from the years 2019-2020, focusing on issues associated with these salient dimensions of Bolsonaro’s political plan.

Finally, we assess the religious discourse as a separate trend. While the use of religion in political life seems to be at odds with the laicity of Brazilian Constitution, it resonates both with conservative views in Brazil and the general beliefs of the majority of the constituency. We are interested, therefore, in assessing if there is any significant difference in the use of religion by Senators across the RILE spectrum.

Senate

General Characteristics

Considering the 26 States plus the Federal District each are entitled to three senates, we would expect the sen_df to have 81 senators, however, Roraima (RR) had one of its senators (Chico Rodrigues) suspended from his activities following an investigation on diversion of resources. For the purposes of this analysis, we will consider the Federal District a State.

The Senate api only displays current senators’ speeches, which is why Roraima only have 2 senators and the corpus only comprises speeches from 80 senators.

In what concerns gender, although females are the majority of Brazilian population (97 males per 100 females), women represent only 1/8 of the composition of the Senate House. 18 States have only male Senators (including Roraima, with only 2 Senators); 8 States have 2 Male Senators and 1 Female Senator and 1 State has 2 Female Senators and 1 Male Senator (Mato Grosso do Sul - MS)

In terms of party distribution, 16 parties have at least one senator in the present term. MDB, PSD and PODEMOS are the parties with largest representation, holding 13, 12 and 10 senators, respectively. All of PSD Senators are male, while PSD and PODEMOS have 1 Female Senator each.

Looking into distribution of gender per party, 9 of these parties have at least one Female Senator; but only 1 party (PP) has 2 Female Senators.

Considering these characteristics of the Senate House, let’s see if the speech distribution follows the same pattern, i.e., let’s check if Females’ are responsible for 1/8 of the total speeches, and how speeches are distributed among these 16 Parties, and among the 27 States.

Gender

We see that women represent 12.5% of the Senate, but are responsible only for 8.79% of the speeches. This result seems consistent with indicators for gender inequality in Brazil, and their effects on women in the workplace.

# Expected frequency of speeches per gender -- based on the number of  senators
expected <-  sen_df %>% 
  group_by(gender) %>% 
  summarise(n = n()) %>% 
  mutate(prop = (n / sum(n))*100) %>% 
  rename(n_sen = n, prop_sen = prop, Gender = gender)

# Observed frequency of speeches
observed <- speech_df  %>% 
  group_by(Gender) %>% 
  summarise(n = n()) %>% 
  mutate(prop = (n / sum(n))*100) %>% 
  rename(n_speech = n, prop_speech = prop)

merge(expected, observed, by = 'Gender') %>% 
  select(Gender, prop_sen, prop_speech) %>% 
  pivot_longer(!Gender, names_to = 'Proportion', values_to = 'Value') %>% 
  mutate(across(is.numeric, ~ round(., 2))) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(Value, Proportion, group = Gender, fill = Gender)) +
  geom_col(position = 'dodge') + 
  geom_text(aes(label = Value), position = position_dodge(0.9), 
            show.legend = FALSE, vjust = -0.5) +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_minimal()

Parties

In what concerns the distribution of speeches per party, we expected MDB, PODEMOS and PSD to have a higher number of speeches, as they account for a larger percentage of the Senate House. What we find out, in fact, is that PT, with only 6 Senators (8% of the Senate House) has 1097 speeches (21% of the speeches). PT was the runner-off party of the 2018 elections and was the party elected for the presidential elections of 2002, 2006, 2010 and 2014. This finding might indicate a higher opposition to Bolsonaro’s agenda within the Senate corpus.

States

Our data set is composed of 5188 speeches given by 80 Senators of 27 States. Assuming each Senator uses speech opportunities equally, we would expect each State to have around 192 speeches. Let’s see if this checks out.

What we see, in fact, is that Senators coming from some States, such as RS, PE, DF and AP far exceed the expected average of speeches; at the same time, Senators from PB, AC and RJ seem not to have spoken as much as their peers in the period of 2019 and 2020.

This might indicate that the items relevant for the agenda of the States that have more speeches might bear higher weight in the corpus.

Speeches Scaling

First, we use Wordfish as the text scaling method for the Senate speeches. After, as shown below, we plot the results of a fitted scaling model.

# Wordfish
wf <- textmodel_wordfish(dfmat_sen, dir = c(16, 6), sparse = TRUE) # PT and PL
textplot_scale1d(wf)

# Data frame with Wordsfish party positions
theta_sen_wf <- as.data.frame(wf$theta, wf$docs) %>% 
    rownames_to_column('party') %>%
    rename(theta_sen_wf = 'wf$theta')

To better understand the Senate speeches position generated with Wordfish, we compare it with the Media perception of each party and with Presidential Manifestos from 2018.

Wordfish Scores X Media

The graph below shows the Brazilian Media categorization (Y-axis) and the Wordfish categorization (X-axis) for each party.

Some parties appear as similar positions in both situations, such as PSB, PSDB, and MDB. On the other hand, the Wordfish model considers PT on the extreme left, around -2 on the scale. In contrast, the Media considers the same party on the left, around -1 on the scale.

We see the same pattern on the other side of the scale. While the Media considers PSL on the right, the Wordfish model assumes the same party in the center position.

#### Parties in 2018’s Presidential Election

The graph illustrates the party positions derived from the Presidential manifestos (Y-axis) and the Senate speeches (X-axis) using wordfish prediction.

It is possible to see a pattern where parties are mostly allocated to the right when using Senate speeches. Although, when analyzing Presidential manifestos, parties are mostly allocated to the left. There is one exception of PDT, which is around the center spectrum on Presidential corpus, and on the extreme left for the Senate corpus.

# austin
# as wfm
wfm_pres <- as.wfm(dfmat_pres, word.margin = 2)

# wordfish pres
wfa_pres <- wordfish(wfm_pres, dir = c(4, 3)) # PSOL, PSL

# match sen features with pres
dfmat_sen_match <- dfm_match(dfmat_sen, featnames(dfmat_pres))

# convert to wfm
wfm_sen <- as.wfm(dfmat_sen_match, word.margin = 2)

# predict values to senate speeches
theta_sen_au <- as.data.frame(predict(wfa_pres, newdata = wfm_sen)) %>%
  rownames_to_column('party') %>%
  rename(theta_sen_au = 'predict(wfa_pres, newdata = wfm_sen)')

# pres scores
theta_pres_au <- as.data.frame(wfa_pres$theta, wfa_pres$docs) %>%
  rownames_to_column('party') %>%
  rename(theta_pres = 'wfa_pres$theta')

# merge dfs -- theta pres and sen
theta_ps <- merge(theta_pres_au, theta_sen_au, by = 'party')

# Compare pres x sen
theta_ps %>% 
  arrange(theta_pres) %>%

Themes

Having assessed how the parties in senate are positioned in the RILE Scale, let’s check how the discussions on the three topics of Bolsonaro’s agenda appear in the Senate House.

For this section, we employed a dictionary analysis, identifying a few words with each topic in order to classify the corpus accordingly.

We initially consulted the “LexiCoder Policy Agenda” dictionary to have a baseline for words that could capture these main topics. We then translated the words to Portuguese and adapted them to the Brazilian context.

In the following sections, we will analyze the three aforementioned dimensions under the topics Economy, Security and Gender & Family.

Dictionary

# Create Dictionary with themes of interest
theme.lexicon <- dictionary(list(economy = c('econom*', 'desempreg*', 'inflação', 'demanda', 'oferta', 'negócios', 'empreg*', 'preço*', 'banco', 'dinheiro', 'gastos', 'dívida', 'juro*', 'control*', 'custo*', 'produtividade', 'índice', 'renda', 'pib', 'produto', 'bruto', 'empreg*', 'trabalh*', 'privat*', 'auxílio', 'desigualdade', 'petróleo', 'petro', 'desigual*', 'custo*', 'capital', 'ações', 'participação', 'aposent*', 'nacionalizar', 'mercado'), genfam = c('famíl*', 'famil*', 'just*', 'mulher*', 'solteir*', 'sex*', 'pai*', 'mãe', 'filh*', 'abort*', 'criança*', 'abrigo', 'gênero', 'gay', 'kit gay', 'jove*', 'juventude', 'tradicional'), security = c('sequestr*', 'inocent*', 'puni*','condena*','sentença', 'tribunal', 'juiz', 'justiça', 'crim*', 'bandid*', 'criminos*', 'ilícit*', 'infrator*', 'impunidade', 'promotor*', 'instância', 'transitado', 'julgado', 'julgamento', 'bala', 'balead*', 'tiro', 'fuzil', 'arma', 'armamento', 'pistola', 'rifle', 'polícia', 'policial', 'militar', 'cidadão de bem', 'cadeia*', 'prisão', 'prisioneir*', 'investigação', 'intervenção militar', 'UPP', 'segurança pública', '*anticrime', '*anti-crime', 'assassin*', 'ladrão', 'vagabund*', 'saidão', 'condicional', 'progressão de regime', 'réu', 'defensoria', 'estupr*', 'traficante*', 'detenção', 'detent*',  'violência', 'reinci*', 'delinquente', 'menor', 'maioridade penal', 'drogas', 'entorpecent*')))

# Create DFM with theme.lexicon, apply weights and convert to data frame
theme_df  <- dfm(corp_sen, dictionary = theme.lexicon) %>% 
    dfm_weight(scheme = 'prop') %>% 
    convert('data.frame')

Scaling

Comparing the economy graph for Wordfish with the main graph, we do not see much difference in party positions. This might suggest that discussions on Economy are the main driver behind the allocation of parties in the RILE spectrum. In other words, views on economic matters could bear a high weight in the definition of where a party is positioned in the ideological spectrum. This suggests that economic discussions are more salient in the corpus.

RILE Features

The graph displays words that push a document farthest to the left or to the right. Words located in the bottom are used less frequently. Right and left word positions range from approximately -2.5 to 2.

The words that most contributed for a left-leaning document are petrobrás (an oil extracting public company whose privatization is a contentious topic), anticapitalista (‘anticapitalist’), cut (‘centralized labour union’), auxílio-doença (‘illness aid’,an employment benefit), sindicalista (‘unionist’) and terceirização (‘outsourcing’). For the right, the words are militarismo (‘militarism’), agroindustriais (‘agribusiness’), grevista (‘striker’), veterinária (‘veterinarian’), logística (‘logistics’) and transportes (‘transport’).

In general, the right discusses agriculture (agribusiness), with words like empreendedorismo (‘entrepeneurship’)/ liberalismo (‘liberalism’), logística (‘logistics’) /infraestrutura (‘infrastructure’).

The left discusses previdência (‘pension benefits’), with words like trabalhadores (‘workers’), direitos (‘rights’), macroeconomia (‘macroeconomics’), sindicalismo (‘trade unionism’).

# Features usage left/right

RILE Features

The graph displays words that push a document farthest to the left or to the right. Words located in the bottom are used less frequently. Right and left word positions range from approximately -1.5 to 1.5.

The words that most contributed for a left-leaning document are defensoria (‘public attorney office’), defensores (‘public attorneys’), direitos (‘rights’), humanos (‘human’), perseguição (‘harassment’), liberdade (‘freedom’) . For the right, the words are vagabundo(s) (‘tramps’), juvenis (‘juvenile’), tropa (‘troop’), pcc (the largest gang in SP), farda (‘police suit’).

In general, the right discusses crime, criminals and law enforcement activities, while the left discusses human rights and judicial harassment.

Interestingly, the use of cadeia (‘jail’) and prisão (‘prison’), which are synonyms in Portuguese, seem associated with speeches in different sides of the RILE spectrum. Similarly, the word vagabundagem (idleness that characterizes a tramp) and vagabundo (s) (‘tramp’) are also associated with different sides of RILE.

Finally, ‘feminicídio’ (a relatively new criminal offense for an aggravated homicide committed against a woman by her former romantic partner), which is a differentiation to standard homicide typically criticized by right wing politicians with a conservative view of gender issues, is the word that appears most strongly associated with a right-leaning political view.

Scaling

Comparing the gender and family graph for Wordfish with the main graph, we see some change in party positions. The party PT is considered extreme left on the main DFM, while left on the genfam DFM. Topics included in gender and family might not be one of the main drivers behind the allocation of parties in the RILE spectrum. Furthermore, this suggests that genfam bears a smaller weight into defining general parties positions, and/or there is a lot of overlap in the genfam vocabulary used by senators across the spectrum.

The word that most contributes for a left-leaning document is resistência (‘resistance’). The words that most contribute to a right-leaning document are tradicional (‘traditional’) and esposa (’wife). All the other words are really close to the center.

Finally, words that we expected to be highly significant don’t even appear in speeches. Some examples are sexista (‘sexist’) and ‘gay’.

Conclusion

From the analyses made in this project, we understand that it is not all the views present in the populist discourse of President Jair Bolsonaro that are also present in the speeches of the Brazilian Senate.

The themes and famous phrases mentioned by the current President, which are mostly propagated by the Media, are not present in the same intensity in the Senate environment. On the other hand, this might be related to the percentage of representation of each party in the Senate. Take PT as an example; it is one of the main opposition parties to Bolsonaro and has a large Senate representation. Thus, most of their speeches are against what is defended by the President.

When analyzing the three main themes highlighted in Bolsonaro’s campaign, the economy is the most present in the Senate. In comparison, security, gender, and family appear less frequently, respectively.
